Good — stable with meters waking confirms the fix is in the right place.

What was wrong (short version)

Two layers:

1. The actual crash — a bug in the Tauri/Wry/WebView stack, not your engines or NVIDIA drivers.
   The procdump showed 0xC000001D inside blackwell-ops.exe on this path:

WebView2 (WebResourceRequested)
     → wry custom_protocol_handler
       → tauri IPC
         → clone Rc<EventLoopRunner>  ← refcount already dead
           → ud2 (illegal instruction)

   That's undefined behavior in the UI bridge — use-after-free on a shared event-loop handle.

2. What triggered it — fusion idle polling created enough background pressure to hit that bug every few minutes.

It wasn't "HTTP crashes the app"

The HTTP calls themselves (GET /slots, GET /metrics to localhost) run in Rust/tokio and don't touch WebView directly.

The chain was:

Per idle engine, every 500ms:
  /slots + /metrics  (2 HTTP requests)
    → parse JSON, update fusion state
      → fusion-update Tauri emit → WebView IPC

With many engines idle at once, that scales badly:

┌───────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ Before        │ 8 idle engines                                    │
├───────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Poll interval │ 500ms                                             │
├───────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Endpoints     │ /slots + /metrics                                 │
├───────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ HTTP rate     │ ~32 req/s                                         │
├───────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ IPC           │ periodic fusion-update even when mostly unchanged │
└───────────────┴───────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

So it wasn't one bad request — it was sustained volume: many engines × frequent polls × JSON work × IPC into WebView. That eventually landed on the fragile Wry/Tauri IPC path and tripped the Rc bug.

Your bisect fit that: BLACKWELL_DISABLE_FUSION_POLL=1 removed the whole loop → no crash. Frontend GPU poll, disk I/O, etc. were fine on their own.

What we changed

Idle engines now use a cheap heartbeat:

• 2.5s tick instead of 500ms
• /health only for 2 ticks, then one /slots sample
• No /metrics while idle
• Full 25ms poll only when actually inferring (PP/TG)
• stderr log belt still drives live meters during real work

That cuts idle load by roughly 20–40× with N engines, which stays under the threshold that was provoking the WebView crash.

What it wasn't

• NVIDIA power management / GPU sleep (possible for stale VRAM, not this exit code)
• llama-server children
• MCP bridge
• Random driver illegal instructions

Bottom line

Bug: Tauri 2.11.x / Wry 0.55.x WebView IPC lifetime issue.
Trigger: fusion idle polling at too high a rate across multiple engines.
Fix: throttle idle polling + cheap heartbeat; keep aggressive polling only during active inference.

Worth filing upstream to tauri-apps/tauri (https://github.com/tauri-apps/tauri) with your procdump if you want a proper framework fix — our change is a solid workaround.

