You're right to treat this as a compromise problem, not a binary choice. I traced the current fusion loop — the crash fix is in the right place, but it introduced a wake latency gap that explains the 1–5s dead meters during agent-style coding sessions.

What’s actually broken (not the active path)

Active inference still polls at 25ms with /slots + /metrics. That path is fine. The pain is getting out of idle:

    fn is_idle_ready(&self) -> bool {
        self.phase == InferencePhase::Idle && self.engine_state == EngineState::Ready
    }

When that’s true, the loop runs the cheap heartbeat:

                    let idle = brain.is_idle_ready();
                    let poll_ms = if idle { poll_idle_ms() } else { poll_active_ms() };
                    // ...
                    if idle && !brain.emit_dirty && idle_cheap_streak < IDLE_CHEAP_HEALTH_STREAK_MAX {
                        if crate::fusion::poller::poll_health_ok(&client, brain.port).await {
                            idle_cheap_streak += 1;
                            // ... heartbeat emit every 10s only
                            continue;  // ← skips /slots entirely
                        }
                    }

Two structural gaps:

1. Log events update brain state but don’t push to the UI immediately

                        BrainInbound::Log(log_event) => {
                            brain.process_log_event(&log_event);
                            brain.emit_dirty = true;
                            idle_cheap_streak = 0;

process_log_event runs (NewPrompt, PP progress, etc.), but emit waits for the next poll tick. If that tick was scheduled as idle, you can wait up to 2.5s even though stderr already told us work started.

2. Cheap heartbeat can skip /slots for 2 consecutive idle ticks

With default BLACKWELL_FUSION_IDLE_POLL_MS=2500 and IDLE_CHEAP_HEALTH_STREAK_MAX=2, a quiet engine (no stderr, Tom stdout-only) can go ~5–7.5s before /slots sees is_processing. That matches “never wakes up” during rapid short reads.

The crash wasn’t “HTTP is dangerous.” It was N idle engines × frequent polls × periodic IPC hammering the Wry refcount bug. One active engine at 25ms was never the problem.

